WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:08.000
From the Library of Congress and the Smithsonian National Museum of African American History and Culture.

00:00:08.000 --> 00:00:19.000
This is Emilye Crosby with Mrs. Peggy Jean Connor and we're at the McCain Library and Archives at the University of Southern Mississippi.

00:00:19.000 --> 00:00:26.000
It's November 30th, 2015 and we're doing this interview as part of the Civil Rights History Project,

00:00:26.000 --> 00:00:35.000
which is co-sponsored by the Library of Congress and the National Smithsonian Museum for African American History and Culture.

00:00:35.000 --> 00:00:38.000
Thank you so much. This is kind of...

00:00:38.000 --> 00:00:53.000
I'm also here with John Bishop and Guha Shankar. Could you start by telling me about your family and when you were born and about growing up here in Hattiesburg?

00:00:54.000 --> 00:01:03.000
I was born in Hattiesburg, Mississippi.

00:01:07.000 --> 00:01:10.000
Then...

00:01:10.000 --> 00:01:27.000
Well, my daddy, he always wanted a doctor for the (he always wanted) a doctor for the birth.

00:01:28.000 --> 00:01:46.000
And when he came, when the doctors would come, they delivered all four of us, all four of us, three siblings and a doctor, Charles Smith.

00:01:47.000 --> 00:02:04.000
My mother was quiet. I think I was in one tank.

00:02:05.000 --> 00:02:19.000
And very shy when I was in school and made good grades, but I never volunteered to ask for nothing.

00:02:20.000 --> 00:02:26.000
And I had a teacher, Ruby M. Tatum.

00:02:26.000 --> 00:02:35.000
I learned later that it was Ruby M. Tatum.

00:02:35.000 --> 00:02:49.000
She taught me seven grades. The first semester was citizenship.

00:02:49.000 --> 00:03:02.000
And then that cheap, really put a lot of emphasis on Ridditch's student to vote.

00:03:03.000 --> 00:03:07.000
That was something in that day.

00:03:07.000 --> 00:03:12.000
And the second semester we had litter too.

00:03:12.000 --> 00:03:25.000
But I remember her telling us, when you get 21 years old, you go to the courthouse, to the circuit clerk's office and Ridditch to the vote.

00:03:25.000 --> 00:03:34.000
And so, that stuck with me, you know, and I started trying to register early.

00:03:34.000 --> 00:03:39.000
It took me about 10 years to become registered.

00:03:39.000 --> 00:03:42.000
Did you try the first time when you were 21?

00:03:42.000 --> 00:03:49.000
I did. And the other thing you had to pay poll tax, two years.

00:03:50.000 --> 00:03:53.000
I mean, yeah, for two years, two dollars.

00:03:53.000 --> 00:04:07.000
Poll tax. And I would pay poll tax. And I would collect poll tax in my beauty shop for patrons that wanted, and it was afraid to go themselves.

00:04:07.000 --> 00:04:20.000
Now, you pay poll tax during the time between January and April, like you paid your taxes before you have to pay penalties on your taxes.

00:04:20.000 --> 00:04:26.000
So, I would take a list of them and just do me all the good in the world.

00:04:26.000 --> 00:04:36.000
When I get there, I was standing, people behind me had the way to, I turned all those, no names, and had receipts for everyone.

00:04:36.000 --> 00:04:39.000
And I just love that.

00:04:39.000 --> 00:04:44.000
So, was this before or after you were in the movie?

00:04:44.000 --> 00:04:51.000
This was before. And after even the movie.

00:04:51.000 --> 00:04:57.000
Well, I'd like to tell how I got in the movie.

00:04:57.000 --> 00:05:06.000
I don't want to rush you ahead, but when you were collecting poll taxes, did a lot of black business owners do that?

00:05:06.000 --> 00:05:08.000
No.

00:05:08.000 --> 00:05:10.000
Who else did you know besides you?

00:05:10.000 --> 00:05:12.000
I didn't know nobody.

00:05:12.000 --> 00:05:15.000
And I just told my customers.

00:05:15.000 --> 00:05:22.000
No. I didn't get the idea to do that.

00:05:22.000 --> 00:05:31.000
Well, I'd been talking and telling them I was going to pay my poll tax because you had to pay two conservative years.

00:05:31.000 --> 00:05:35.000
And if you miss a year, you had to start all over again.

00:05:35.000 --> 00:05:47.000
And I would tell them, you know, and I talked to them and they would tell some people and get a list and take a day.

00:05:47.000 --> 00:05:51.000
They must have been unhappy to see you coming.

00:05:51.000 --> 00:05:56.000
I didn't go every day, but they knew me.

00:05:56.000 --> 00:05:59.000
So, who, you said that's a circuit plate?

00:05:59.000 --> 00:06:01.000
Which office was that?

00:06:01.000 --> 00:06:06.000
That was the voter registration officer.

00:06:06.000 --> 00:06:10.000
So it was like Mr. Theron Lynd, it was the office where he was?

00:06:10.000 --> 00:06:12.000
It's the same office.

00:06:12.000 --> 00:06:14.000
Did they ever try to intimidate you?

00:06:14.000 --> 00:06:17.000
No, nobody.

00:06:17.000 --> 00:06:19.000
Nobody really bothered me.

00:06:19.000 --> 00:06:26.000
I guess I looked like a little girl, you know, and they never looked at me.

00:06:26.000 --> 00:06:35.000
They didn't realize how much trouble you could...

00:06:35.000 --> 00:06:40.000
I didn't know how much trouble I could.

00:06:40.000 --> 00:06:44.000
What did your parents do for a living?

00:06:44.000 --> 00:06:55.000
Well, my mother, at that time, she was just a housewife and took care of kids.

00:06:55.000 --> 00:07:00.000
And my daddy worked at a lumber yard.

00:07:00.000 --> 00:07:05.000
He taught him lumber yard and then he got kind of elevated and he got...

00:07:05.000 --> 00:07:19.000
He went to the cricket pit house and drive the owner to town and out on the coast of wherever he was going.

00:07:19.000 --> 00:07:22.000
So he was like a show-off.

00:07:22.000 --> 00:07:25.000
Was that a good job?

00:07:25.000 --> 00:07:32.000
Well, it was okay when paying a whole lot.

00:07:32.000 --> 00:07:38.000
I don't think he made much more than he was making when he was working in the lumber yard.

00:07:38.000 --> 00:07:49.000
And then he would get up early, go to bed early, and then get up like about two o'clock and go wash your windows all downtown.

00:07:49.000 --> 00:07:55.000
Yeah, I'm all just about all the business downtown he washed your windows.

00:07:55.000 --> 00:08:05.000
So he made a living, you might say.

00:08:05.000 --> 00:08:14.000
But after I got larger, well, I started my aunt had a beauty shop.

00:08:14.000 --> 00:08:23.000
And in fact, she gave me her beauty shop when she left Hattiesburg.

00:08:23.000 --> 00:08:29.000
That's how I become owner of my shop.

00:08:29.000 --> 00:08:35.000
She...

00:08:35.000 --> 00:08:43.000
I was the extra brick, brick, brick, brick, and I'm a fly home.

00:08:43.000 --> 00:08:47.000
Because I didn't consider myself that.

00:08:47.000 --> 00:08:49.000
I was just doing my part.

00:08:49.000 --> 00:08:56.000
I thought my sister told me once that she said,

00:08:56.000 --> 00:08:59.000
I wanted to go to all-con.

00:08:59.000 --> 00:09:04.000
And I asked Daddy, could I go with the group that was going from Hattiesburg,

00:09:05.000 --> 00:09:13.000
And he told me, asking, and that's when both of us come to Hattisbury.

00:09:13.000 --> 00:09:19.000
So I helped take care of my siblings.

00:09:19.000 --> 00:09:27.000
So your father was recognizing your contribution and I know that he had to be okay with you?

00:09:27.000 --> 00:09:31.000
Was that usual at the time?

00:09:32.000 --> 00:09:36.000
I didn't know nothing about.

00:09:36.000 --> 00:09:38.000
He would tell them.

00:09:38.000 --> 00:09:41.000
Like I said, it's been...

00:09:41.000 --> 00:09:48.000
I know that she told me that.

00:09:48.000 --> 00:09:51.000
I didn't know he had told me.

00:09:51.000 --> 00:09:54.000
How many were you when you started working at your aunt's?

00:09:54.000 --> 00:09:56.000
11.

00:09:56.000 --> 00:09:58.000
And I got 10 cents a shampoo.

00:09:58.000 --> 00:10:00.000
I was a shampoo girl.

00:10:00.000 --> 00:10:04.000
I got 10 cents if I ever shampooed.

00:10:04.000 --> 00:10:07.000
And she was a tough sister.

00:10:07.000 --> 00:10:16.000
She would make me think what the lady had on and what she talked about.

00:10:16.000 --> 00:10:23.000
I had to tell her, well she would give me a ticket.

00:10:23.000 --> 00:10:26.000
And she write a name on it and I give it back to her.

00:10:26.000 --> 00:10:28.000
She had to take it.

00:10:28.000 --> 00:10:31.000
She gave it to me.

00:10:31.000 --> 00:10:34.000
But I didn't say a word.

00:10:34.000 --> 00:10:37.000
I just go on and do it.

00:10:37.000 --> 00:10:40.000
And so she gave me the beauty school.

00:10:40.000 --> 00:10:43.000
She had a beauty school.

00:10:43.000 --> 00:10:48.000
And I graduated from beauty school in 1946.

00:10:48.000 --> 00:10:50.000
It was her school?

00:10:50.000 --> 00:10:51.000
Her school.

00:10:51.000 --> 00:10:54.000
So she had the shop at the school?

00:10:54.000 --> 00:10:58.000
She didn't charge you for going to the school.

00:10:58.000 --> 00:11:00.000
So I guess even though she was tough on you.

00:11:00.000 --> 00:11:04.000
She recognized your contribution.

00:11:04.000 --> 00:11:05.000
I guess so.

00:11:05.000 --> 00:11:09.000
How did you feel about your work when you were 11?

00:11:09.000 --> 00:11:10.000
Did you enjoy it?

00:11:10.000 --> 00:11:14.000
I enjoyed it.

00:11:14.000 --> 00:11:18.000
I didn't get a chance to go to a lot of school flunk.

00:11:18.000 --> 00:11:21.000
She didn't because I was working.

00:11:21.000 --> 00:11:23.000
But it didn't bother me.

00:11:23.000 --> 00:11:26.000
And then I was going to post for talking.

00:11:26.000 --> 00:11:28.000
Yes.

00:11:28.000 --> 00:11:34.000
But she was married to a minister.

00:11:34.000 --> 00:11:41.000
And she was kind of, I think, heading her mind.

00:11:41.000 --> 00:11:43.000
She was going to be one day.

00:11:43.000 --> 00:11:47.000
I said, so it wasn't too much gossiping went on.

00:11:47.000 --> 00:11:51.000
She had a lot of the magazines and things.

00:11:51.000 --> 00:11:57.000
And she had to read and run too much gossiping.

00:11:57.000 --> 00:12:00.000
Did she really, because that's how there were many women

00:12:00.000 --> 00:12:02.000
that were ministers?

00:12:02.000 --> 00:12:03.000
No.

00:12:03.000 --> 00:12:06.000
But she would, missionaries, they would...

00:12:06.000 --> 00:12:09.000
That idea.

00:12:09.000 --> 00:12:12.000
Well, you just told me she was married to a minister.

00:12:12.000 --> 00:12:15.000
What kind of work did he do?

00:12:15.000 --> 00:12:16.000
Carpenter.

00:12:16.000 --> 00:12:18.000
He was a carpenter.

00:12:18.000 --> 00:12:25.000
And he decided with some of his members,

00:12:25.000 --> 00:12:29.000
he was from a place called Farm Habermy, Mississippi.

00:12:29.000 --> 00:12:32.000
I from Canton, Mississippi.

00:12:32.000 --> 00:12:37.000
And they were holding this people.

00:12:37.000 --> 00:12:43.000
And my grandmother was of the Church of God.

00:12:43.000 --> 00:12:46.000
And my mother's mother.

00:12:46.000 --> 00:12:59.000
And he met my aunt who was in Houston, Texas.

00:12:59.000 --> 00:13:02.000
And they got married.

00:13:02.000 --> 00:13:04.000
They moved back to Mississippi.

00:13:04.000 --> 00:13:05.000
Is that your mother's sister?

00:13:05.000 --> 00:13:07.000
My mother's sister.

00:13:07.000 --> 00:13:10.000
My mother's brother on the beauty school,

00:13:10.000 --> 00:13:15.000
Franklin Beauty School, in that day.

00:13:15.000 --> 00:13:18.000
So it's really a family business in some ways?

00:13:18.000 --> 00:13:19.000
Yes.

00:13:19.000 --> 00:13:22.000
It's a lot of beauticians.

00:13:22.000 --> 00:13:23.000
And I remember.

00:13:23.000 --> 00:13:27.000
I had a picture at home.

00:13:27.000 --> 00:13:32.000
It was taken in the 70s.

00:13:32.000 --> 00:13:35.000
And all sitting at the table.

00:13:35.000 --> 00:13:39.000
And I said, a family of beauticians.

00:13:39.000 --> 00:13:41.000
Was everybody kin to you?

00:13:41.000 --> 00:13:43.000
Yeah, everybody.

00:13:43.000 --> 00:13:44.000
It was family.

00:13:44.000 --> 00:13:49.000
So did, was it different shops?

00:13:49.000 --> 00:13:50.000
Were they like Hattiesburg?

00:13:50.000 --> 00:13:53.000
Oh no, he had it.

00:13:53.000 --> 00:13:58.000
It was all over Texas in the latter.

00:13:58.000 --> 00:14:03.000
We thought he was rich.

00:14:03.000 --> 00:14:08.000
He walked, we found him and he died.

00:14:08.000 --> 00:14:11.000
So did you ever think about doing any other line of work

00:14:11.000 --> 00:14:15.000
or did it just seem natural to follow your aunt?

00:14:15.000 --> 00:14:18.000
It just seemed natural.

00:14:18.000 --> 00:14:20.000
Because if you'd work in the home,

00:14:20.000 --> 00:14:23.000
she wouldn't make it in her money.

00:14:23.000 --> 00:14:28.000
A lot of people were making $2 a day.

00:14:29.000 --> 00:14:36.000
And then when I worked in the shop,

00:14:36.000 --> 00:14:39.000
I wouldn't like people that stayed at home

00:14:39.000 --> 00:14:42.000
and they didn't get the, I got the Fah price.

00:14:42.000 --> 00:14:47.000
She told me you've been that athletic.

00:14:47.000 --> 00:14:52.000
So I was getting the same thing she was getting.

00:14:52.000 --> 00:14:55.000
Even when you were younger?

00:14:55.000 --> 00:14:59.000
So did she let you set your own price while you were like

00:14:59.000 --> 00:15:01.000
when you started doing your own?

00:15:01.000 --> 00:15:02.000
No.

00:15:02.000 --> 00:15:03.000
Okay.

00:15:03.000 --> 00:15:08.000
So whoever came in the shop, they picked what was on the earth.

00:15:08.000 --> 00:15:12.000
What were your pounds like?

00:15:12.000 --> 00:15:17.000
My daddy was a strict man.

00:15:17.000 --> 00:15:20.000
And we walked the line.

00:15:20.000 --> 00:15:23.000
I tell you that, three girls.

00:15:23.000 --> 00:15:29.000
And he was going to make a bow out of that one,

00:15:29.000 --> 00:15:33.000
one, one, uh, son he had.

00:15:33.000 --> 00:15:37.000
So he had to mow yard.

00:15:37.000 --> 00:15:42.000
You know, and we would get out there and hit him.

00:15:42.000 --> 00:15:46.000
So he tried to be, this is what the boys do

00:15:46.000 --> 00:15:48.000
and this is what the girls do.

00:15:48.000 --> 00:15:51.000
Just mix it up.

00:15:51.000 --> 00:15:55.000
You did say that you three girls spoiled your baby brother.

00:15:55.000 --> 00:15:57.000
That's right.

00:15:57.000 --> 00:15:58.000
It's more than right.

00:15:58.000 --> 00:16:00.000
You enjoyed that?

00:16:00.000 --> 00:16:02.000
Yeah, I really did.

00:16:02.000 --> 00:16:04.000
Enjoy it.

00:16:04.000 --> 00:16:07.000
Did your mother ever work out as high as the house?

00:16:07.000 --> 00:16:08.000
She did.

00:16:08.000 --> 00:16:11.000
My daddy took seat.

00:16:11.000 --> 00:16:15.000
And she did work some out of the house

00:16:15.000 --> 00:16:18.000
when he got sick.

00:16:18.000 --> 00:16:23.000
And she worked for people and they didn't have no more than we had.

00:16:23.000 --> 00:16:26.000
And when she gets to working,

00:16:26.000 --> 00:16:29.000
I don't have any money.

00:16:29.000 --> 00:16:32.000
Do you want this radio?

00:16:32.000 --> 00:16:34.000
You want this?

00:16:34.000 --> 00:16:39.000
You want, you know, and that was her way of paying.

00:16:39.000 --> 00:16:43.000
And we were glad to get to read here.

00:16:43.000 --> 00:16:45.000
This is white families?

00:16:45.000 --> 00:16:50.000
Yeah, white families.

00:16:50.000 --> 00:16:52.000
What did your parents teach you?

00:16:52.000 --> 00:16:54.000
You mentioned that teacher who taught...

00:16:54.000 --> 00:17:00.000
I'm trying to think I didn't know Mississippi allowed the black schools to teach citizenship.

00:17:00.000 --> 00:17:03.000
We had it.

00:17:03.000 --> 00:17:07.000
And a young lady that was ahead of me,

00:17:07.000 --> 00:17:11.000
days away, she died back not too long ago.

00:17:11.000 --> 00:17:18.000
She don't even remember having citizenship when she was a great head of me.

00:17:18.000 --> 00:17:24.000
But we had citizenship.

00:17:24.000 --> 00:17:26.000
Do you know if your teacher was registered?

00:17:26.000 --> 00:17:28.000
She was.

00:17:28.000 --> 00:17:31.000
That's one thing she did not tell us.

00:17:31.000 --> 00:17:33.000
She wasn't.

00:17:33.000 --> 00:17:35.000
Did she try, do you know?

00:17:35.000 --> 00:17:37.000
I got registered.

00:17:37.000 --> 00:17:39.000
I went to her.

00:17:39.000 --> 00:17:41.000
She had retired, then,

00:17:41.000 --> 00:17:43.000
and asked her about going,

00:17:43.000 --> 00:17:46.000
she said, oh, I'm not going through the book there.

00:17:46.000 --> 00:17:48.000
Did you remind her?

00:17:48.000 --> 00:17:50.000
I told her.

00:17:50.000 --> 00:17:54.000
She said, well, I did do something good, didn't I?

00:17:54.000 --> 00:17:57.000
She was a good teacher.

00:17:57.000 --> 00:17:58.000
She.

00:17:58.000 --> 00:18:01.000
In literature too.

00:18:01.000 --> 00:18:05.000
Did she say why she wasn't done?

00:18:05.000 --> 00:18:08.000
I knew who I, you know.

00:18:08.000 --> 00:18:11.000
Was this in the early days?

00:18:11.000 --> 00:18:13.000
This was, you know, well,

00:18:13.000 --> 00:18:20.000
see, I didn't get registered until...

00:18:20.000 --> 00:18:26.000
I want to say...

00:18:26.000 --> 00:18:29.000
I want to say it was in 1770.

00:18:29.000 --> 00:18:34.000
I'm not sure, but it was way out there.

00:18:34.000 --> 00:18:36.000
I think it's been time for...

00:18:36.000 --> 00:18:39.000
Was it after the voting right act?

00:18:39.000 --> 00:18:42.000
The voting right act came in 65-

